a palpable 3 cm tender red swelling in the natal cleft.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound examination","MRI pelvis","Antibiotics and review in one week","Fine needle aspiration","Incision and drainage"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA painful, reddened and tender swelling in the subcutaneous tissue is an abscess. Given the site of this lesion, it is a pilonidal abscess. This is a clinical diagnosis and does not need any imaging to aid making the diagnosis, therefore \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound examination \u003C/strong\u003Eor \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is not generally used for treatment of superficial abscesses except in the breast given the high rate of recurrence, difficulty aspirating thick purulent fluid and need to break down loculations. This might be applicable for intra-abdominal collections, but not superficial lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntibiotics alone are unlikely to penetrate into an abscess cavity, therefore \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotics and review in one week\u003C/strong\u003E for an established abscess is not appropriate. Antibiotics might be applicable as an adjunct to definitive treatment if the patient was at risk of spreading infection. Such cases might include the immunocompromised or the presence of a prosthesis, such as a heart valve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncision and drainage \u003C/strong\u003Eis the recommended treatment. This allows complete drainage and washout of the infected cavity and allows placement of antibacterial gauze in the abscess cavity. The patient should be encouraged to use regular sitz baths to facilitate healing by second intention. Pilonidal sinuses are prone to recurrent infection and the patient may need formal excision of the sinus at some stage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pilonidal abscess is a common presentation to the Emergency Department, General Practice and in General Surgery. It is diganosed clinically and requires incision and drainage."],"references":["Gil LA, Deans KJ, Minneci PC. Management of Pilonidal Disease A Review. JAMA Surg. doi:10.1001/jamasurg.2023.0373"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27933"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1185"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27933"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-26T14:54:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-26T14:54:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1185"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42956"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"d